    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-approxint">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 6.5</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Approximate definite integrals using the midpoint rule.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Approximate definite integrals using the trapezoidal rule.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Approximate definite integrals using Simpson's rule.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Estimate the error in approximating a definite integral.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>


      <page>
        <!-- div attr= class="problems"-->
        <exercise xml:id="ex-approxint-ln2">
          <introduction>
            <p> In this exercise we will make several estimates of <me>
                \ln 2 = \int_1^2 \frac{1}{x} \,dx.
              </me>
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
              <p>Estimate <m>\ln 2</m> with the Trapezoidal Rule and <m>n=8</m> subdivisions.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
            <p> We have <m>\Delta x = \frac{1}{8}</m>, and the list of points is <me>\set{x_0,x_1,x_2,\dots,x_7,x_8}
              = \set{1,\frac{9}{8},\frac{10}{8},\dots,\frac{15}{8},2}</me> So <me>\begin{split}
                T_8 &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{8}\left(
                1 \cdot \frac{8}{8} +
                2 \cdot \frac{8}{9} +
                2 \cdot \frac{8}{10} + \dotsm
                2 \cdot \frac{8}{15} +
                1 \cdot \frac{8}{16}\right) \\
                &amp;= \frac{200,107}{288,288} \approx 0.694122
                \end{split}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
              <p>Estimate <m>\ln 2</m> with the Midpoint Rule and <m>n=8</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> This time the set of midpoints is <me>
                \set{\frac{17}{16},\frac{19}{16},\frac{21}{16},\dots,\frac{29}{16},\frac{31}{16}}</me>
                So we get <me>\begin{split}
                  M_8 &amp;= \frac{1}{8}\left(
                \frac{16}{17}+\frac{16}{19}+\frac{16}{21}+\dots+\frac{16}{29}+\frac{16}{31}\right)
                  \\
                  &amp;= \frac{21,858,095,488}{31,556,720,475}
                  \approx0.692661.
                  \end{split}</me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
              <p>Estimate <m>\ln 2</m> with Simpson’s rule and <m>n=4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> This time we are adding up roughly half as many points: <me>\begin{split}
                  S_4 &amp;= \frac{1}{3} \frac{1}{4}
                  \left(1 \cdot \frac{4}{4}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{5}{4}
                  + 2 \cdot \frac{6}{4}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{7}{4}
                  + 1 \cdot \frac{8}{4}\right) \\
                  &amp;= \frac{1747}{2520} \approx 0.693254
                  \end{split}</me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
              <p> Estimate <m>\ln 2</m> with Simpson’s rule and <m>n=8</m>. </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <me>\begin{split}
                  S_8 &amp;= \frac{1}{3} \cdot\frac{1}{8}
                  \left(1 \cdot \frac{8}{8}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{8}{9}
                  + 2 \cdot \frac{8}{10}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{8}{11}
                  + 2 \cdot \frac{8}{12}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{8}{13}
                  + 2 \cdot \frac{8}{14}
                  + 4 \cdot \frac{8}{15}
                  + 1 \cdot \frac{8}{16}\right) \\
                  &amp;= \frac{1498711}{2162160} \approx 0.693155
                  \end{split}</me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <conclusion>
            <p>
              Compare your answers with a calculator result and note the accuracy.
            </p>
          </conclusion>
        </exercise>
      </page>
      <page>
        <exercise xml:id="ex-approxint-ln2-estimates">
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Of course, the calculator's answer is only an estimate too.
              The error bound results in the text tell us truly how close
              our estimates are.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task workspace="2in">
            <statement >
              <p>Estimate the maximum error in our approximation of <m>\ln 2</m> with the Midpoint
                Rule and <m>n=4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>f''(x) = \frac{2}{x^3}</m>, which is <m>\leq 2</m> on <m>[1,2]</m>. So <me>\abs{EM_4}
                \leq \frac{2}{24\cdot 16} = \frac{1}{192} \approx 0.0052</me> So the accuracy is
                somewhere between two and three decimal places. </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="2in">
            <statement>
              <p> How many divisions would we need to get <m>\ln
                  2</m> correct within <m>10^{-10}</m> using the Midpoint Rule? </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> For <m>f(x) =
                  \frac{1}{x}</m> on <m>[1,2]</m> we have <m>\abs{EM_n} \leq \frac{1}{12n^2}</m>. To
                ensure that <m>\abs{EM_n} &lt; 10^{-10}</m>, it suffices to ensure that <me>\frac{1}{12n^2}
                &lt;
                  10^{-10}
                  \implies
                  \frac{10^{10}}{12} &lt; n^2
                  \implies
                  n &gt; \frac{10^5}{2\sqrt{3}} = \frac{5 \times 10^4}{\sqrt{3}}.</me> Since <m>\frac{5}{\sqrt{3}}
                &lt; 3</m>, it suffices to take <m>n &gt; 3 \times 10^4 =30,000</m>. We get <me>M_{30000}
                \approx 0.693147180525223</me>, while Mathematica tells me that <m>\ln 2</m> to 15
                decimal places is <me>\ln 2 \approx 0.693147180559945</me> So we do have agreement
                up to ten decimal places. </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="2in">
            <statement>
              <p> How many divisions would we need to get <m>\ln 2</m> correct to within <m>
                  10^{-10}</m> using Simpson’s Rule? </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> This time <m>f^{(4)}(x) = -\frac{24}{x^5}</m>, so <m>\abs{f^{(4)}(x)}
                  \leq 24</m> on <m>[1,2]</m>. Thus <me>\abs{ES_n} \leq \frac{24}{180 n^4} =
                \frac{2}{15n^4}.</me> In order to ensure that <m>\abs{ES_n} \leq 10^{-10}</m>, it
                suffices to ensure that <me>\frac{2}{15n^4}
                  &lt; 10^{-10}
                  \implies
                  n^4 &gt; \frac{2 \times 10^{10}}{15}
                  \implies
                  n &gt;\sqrt[4]{\frac{2}{15}} \times 100 \sqrt{10}
                  = \sqrt[4]{\frac{200}{15}} \times 100</me> Since <m>\frac{200}{15}</m> is between <m>
                1</m> and <m>16</m>, we estimate <m>\sqrt[4]{\frac{200}{15}} &lt; 2</m>. So we can
                take <m>n=200</m> and we should be OK. <me>S_{200} \approx 0.693147180579475</me>
                and indeed we have the right amount of accuracy in much smaller time! </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </exercise>
      </page>
    </worksheet>
